# First-Time Setup Guide

## When to trigger setup

**If you are in the core repo** (repo name is `design-core` and git origin points to `ubrandon/design-core`): the user is a developer maintaining the tool. **Do not run this setup flow** — skip it entirely and follow `design-tool.mdc` in core repo mode.

Check if the file `.designer` exists in the repo root. If it **does not exist**, the user has not completed setup yet. When they ask to "set up" or "get started" or paste a getting-started prompt, walk them through the setup flow below.

If `.designer` already exists, setup is done -- skip this entirely and follow the normal `design-tool.mdc` rules.

## Detecting setup type

There are two setup paths:

- **Company setup** -- the user is the first person at their org setting up Design Core. They need the full setup: clone the public repo, create a new company repo on GitHub, connect them, identity, team members. Detect this when: they say "setting up for my company" or "first time", or their prompt uses the company setup prompt from GETTING_STARTED.md.
- **Designer joining** -- the user's company already has a Design Core repo. They just clone their company's repo and set up their identity. Detect this when: they say "joining my team" or their prompt uses the designer joining prompt from GETTING_STARTED.md, or git origin already points to a company repo (not `ubrandon/design-core`).

If unclear, ask: "Are you setting this up for your company for the first time, or joining a team that already has it?"

## Setup flow

Walk the user through these steps conversationally. Ask one thing at a time -- don't dump everything at once. Be friendly and non-technical.

### 1. Collect company info

Ask these two questions (one at a time):

1. **"What's your company or team name?"** (e.g. `Acme Design`)
2. **"What's your GitHub organization or account name?"** (e.g. `acme-design`) -- where the new repo will live.

The new repo will be named **`design-core-<company-slug>`** (lowercase, hyphenated). Examples: "Jack Henry" → `design-core-jack-henry`, "Acme Design" → `design-core-acme-design`.

### 2. Ensure tools are available

The setup needs `git`, `node`, `npm`, and `gh` (GitHub CLI). Check for each and install any that are missing:

1. **git** -- run `git --version`. Should already be installed. If not, on macOS: `xcode-select --install`.
2. **Node.js** -- run `node --version`. If missing, on macOS: `brew install node`. Otherwise: download from [nodejs.org](https://nodejs.org).
3. **gh (GitHub CLI)** -- run `gh --version`. If missing, install it: on macOS: `brew install gh`. Otherwise: see [cli.github.com](https://cli.github.com).
4. **gh auth** -- run `gh auth status`. If not logged in, run `gh auth login` and walk the user through the prompts (browser login is easiest).

### 3. Clone, create company repo, and connect

**Critical:** The public repo (`ubrandon/design-core`) is **never modified**. We clone it, create a new company repo, and point the clone at the new repo. The public repo stays as an upstream so the company can pull updates later.

Run these steps automatically:

1. **Clone the public repo** with the company name:
   ```
   git clone https://github.com/ubrandon/design-core.git design-core-COMPANY_SLUG
   ```
   This creates a local folder (e.g. `design-core-jack-henry`) with all the tool files.

2. **Create a new empty repo** on GitHub under their org/account:
   ```
   gh repo create THEIR_ORG/design-core-COMPANY_SLUG --private --description "Design Core for COMPANY_NAME"
   ```
   (Use `--public` if they prefer a public repo. Omit `THEIR_ORG/` and use just the repo name if creating under a personal account.)

3. **Swap remotes** so the clone points to the new repo and keeps the public repo as upstream:
   ```
   cd design-core-COMPANY_SLUG
   git remote rename origin upstream
   git remote add origin https://github.com/THEIR_ORG/design-core-COMPANY_SLUG.git
   ```
   Now `origin` = their company repo (push here), `upstream` = public repo (pull updates from here).

4. **Install dependencies:**
   ```
   npm install
   ```

5. **Update `GETTING_STARTED.md`** -- replace `YOUR_ORG` and `YOUR_REPO` with the company's org and repo name so teammates get the right clone URL.

6. **Update `.designer.example`** with the company name (see step 5 below for the format).

7. **Commit and push** to the new company repo:
   ```
   git add -A
   git commit -m "Set up Design Core for COMPANY_NAME"
   git push -u origin main
   ```

8. **Enable GitHub Pages** (optional, for shareable prototype links):
   ```
   gh api repos/THEIR_ORG/design-core-COMPANY_SLUG/pages -X POST -f build_type=workflow
   ```
   If it succeeds, prototypes will be live at `https://THEIR_ORG.github.io/design-core-COMPANY_SLUG/` after each push. If it fails, tell the user to enable it manually: repo **Settings → Pages → Source → GitHub Actions**.

### Pulling updates from the public repo later

To get updates from the public Design Core repo at any time:
```
git fetch upstream
git merge upstream/main
```

### For designers joining (skip steps 1–3 above)

Designers joining an existing team just clone the company repo directly. There's no fork or repo creation — the admin already did that. They only need identity setup (step 5 below).

### 4. Check Cursor settings

Before going further, remind the user to set up Cursor for the best experience:

- **Agent mode** should be active (it's the default in the chat panel). This lets the AI create files, run commands, and build things for them.
- **Model set to Auto** -- tell them to check the model dropdown at the bottom of the chat and pick **Auto**. It's the fastest and cheapest option.

### 5. Collect identity info

#### Company setup (first person at the org)

You already have the company name from step 1. Now ask:

1. **"What's your name?"** -- their display name for attribution on projects
2. **"Who else is on your design team?"** -- optional, they can add people later. If they provide names, collect them.

Create `.designer` in the repo root:

```json
{
  "name": "Their Name",
  "company": "Their Company",
  "team": [
    { "name": "Their Name" },
    { "name": "Teammate 1" },
    { "name": "Teammate 2" }
  ]
}
```

Also update `.designer.example` so future teammates see the right format with the company name pre-filled:

```json
{
  "name": "Your Name",
  "company": "Their Company",
  "team": [
    { "name": "Your Name" }
  ]
}
```

Commit the updated `.designer.example` to git so teammates get it when they clone.

#### Designer joining (team already exists)

Ask the user:

1. **"What's your name?"** -- their display name for attribution

Read `.designer.example` to get the company name and pre-fill it. If the example file doesn't have a company name, ask them.

Create `.designer` in the repo root:

```json
{
  "name": "Their Name",
  "company": "Company from .designer.example",
  "team": [
    { "name": "Their Name" }
  ]
}
```

The team array only needs them -- they don't need to list the whole org. The `company` field should match what the admin set up.

### 6. Start the preview server

Run `npm run dev` and tell them the URL to open in their browser. Explain what they'll see: the home page with a project hub.

### 7. Offer next steps

#### For company setup

> "You're all set! A few things you might want to do:
> - **Create your first project** -- just tell me a name and I'll set it up
> - **Share with your team** -- send them the Getting Started page on your repo: `https://github.com/THEIR_ORG/THEIR_REPO_NAME/blob/main/GETTING_STARTED.md` -- the designer joining prompt already has your org's repo link.
> - **Explore the design system** -- click Design System in the nav to see available components
>
> What would you like to do first?"

#### For designer joining

> "You're all set! Here's what you can do:
> - **Create a project** -- just tell me a name and I'll set it up
> - **Look at existing projects** -- check the home page to see what your team has built
> - **Explore the design system** -- click Design System in the nav to see available components
>
> What would you like to build?"

## Important notes

- The `.designer` file is gitignored -- each person on the team creates their own when they first set up
- `.designer.example` IS committed to git -- the admin updates it with the company name so new designers get it pre-filled
- `GETTING_STARTED.md` IS committed to git -- the admin updates it with their org's repo URL so designers get the right clone link
- The `company` field helps the AI understand the team context
- The `team` array is a local reference -- each person's file only needs their own name (the admin's file may list everyone)
- Do NOT commit `.designer` to git. Only `.designer.example` gets committed.

## Tool updates belong in the core repo ONLY

**NEVER make tool-level changes in a company repo.** Company repos pull tool updates from the upstream core repo (`ubrandon/design-core`) via `git fetch upstream && git merge upstream/main`. If you edit tool files (Cursor rules, root HTML pages, scripts, styles, config, docs) directly in a company repo, those changes will conflict with future upstream merges.

The only tool-level files modified in a company repo are `GETTING_STARTED.md` and `.designer.example` -- and only during the initial setup commit (step 3.5 and 3.6 above). After that, all tool changes flow from the core repo downstream.
